<ns6161:section xmlns:ns6161="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.classes.innerClasses.innerClasses">
  
    <ns6162:title xmlns:ns6162="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Inner Classes</ns6162:title>

<ns6163:para xmlns:ns6163="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Non-static (instance) nested classes are commonly referred to as <ns6164:emphasis xmlns:ns6164="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="em"> inner
classes</ns6164:emphasis>. Unlike nested classes, inner classes have access to the instance
variables of the outer class instance. Like static
nested classes, inner classes are defined either within another class or
within a method of another class or within a block of a method of another
class.
</ns6163:para>
<ns6165:para xmlns:ns6165="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The difference between nested and inner classes can be summarized as follows:
<ns6166:itemizedlist xmlns:ns6166="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <ns6167:listitem xmlns:ns6167="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns6168:para xmlns:ns6168="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> A <ns6169:emphasis xmlns:ns6169="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="em"> nested class</ns6169:emphasis> is a class is a member of the outer class.</ns6168:para></ns6167:listitem>
  <ns6170:listitem xmlns:ns6170="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns6171:para xmlns:ns6171="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> An instance of an inner class exists within the context of an
        instance of the outer class.</ns6171:para></ns6170:listitem>
</ns6166:itemizedlist>
</ns6165:para>
<ns6172:para xmlns:ns6172="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">One typically would define an inner class when
<ns6173:itemizedlist xmlns:ns6173="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <ns6174:listitem xmlns:ns6174="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns6175:para xmlns:ns6175="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> it is only useful for the context (class, method or method block)
        in which it is defined.</ns6175:para></ns6174:listitem>
   <ns6176:listitem xmlns:ns6176="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns6177:para xmlns:ns6177="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">the inner class should have access to the instance members of
        the outer class in whose context it is defined.</ns6177:para></ns6176:listitem>
</ns6173:itemizedlist>
</ns6172:para>    
    
